**Refining MSFT Strategy**

I'm now zeroing in on MSFT. My assessment of the market has yielded a bearish thesis that includes an anticipated 16% pullback. I have identified a more tactical profit target near the 200-day SMA at $474.50, moving beyond my original $640 median. I have started examining the MSFT option chain for Feb 2026 to see if a vertical spread is a viable approach. Also, I am now thinking I will ignore the "falling knife" setup on AAPL. The macro signals are supportive of a moderate position, even though the bullish/bearish ratio is not quite there, currently at 0.25 (need >0.3). I've been evaluating the current market indicators. Right now, my portfolio is empty. Macro signals are strongly bullish, pointing towards a high probability of a Fed rate cut and low uncertainty. The technicals suggest an oversold condition; RSI is at 32.8 and stochastic is at 7.3, both indicating extreme oversold territory.

**Deciding On Position**

I'm now leaning bullish. AAPL looks attractive given the recent signals; the bearish structural issues still exist, but the strong RPO growth and bullish divergence in the MACD are compelling. I'm targeting a 10% position with a swing strategy and a stop-loss at 2.5x ATR below my entry around $460.50. My take profit target is either $474.50 (SMA200) or $480. Given that MSFT earnings are approaching, and the current date, I'll reduce the position size to 5% of equity (half of normal position).

**Solidifying My MSFT Position**

I'm now fully committed to a 10% long position in MSFT, given my high conviction. My entry is now set, and I've established both stop-loss and take-profit levels at $455.37 and $480.00 respectively. This swing trade leverages strong RPO growth and bullish MACD divergence within a highly supportive macro environment, with a 94% probability of a Fed rate cut. AAPL and GOOGL will be held, but not acted upon.

I've been further refining my rationale for the MSFT position. I've considered the value/quality factor, drawing on Fama-French (1992), and concluded that the RPO growth provides a strong signal.
